s offers a series of discontinuous but probing studies of the forms their participation takes. This collection presents the work of a wide range of scholars, critics, and thinkers from diverse disciplines: philosophy, literature, history, geography, economics, art history, cultural studies, and the visual arts. By approaching animals from such different perspectives, these essays broaden the scope of animal studies to include specialists and nonspecialists alike, inviting readers from all backgrounds to consider the place of animals in history and art. Combining provocative critical insights with arresting visual imagery, Gorgeous Beasts advances a challenging new appreciation of animals as co-inhabitants and co-creators of culture.Aside from the editors, the contributors are Dean Bavington, Ron Broglio, Mark Dion, Erica Fudge, Cecilia Novero, Harriet Ritvo, Nigel Rothfels, Sajay Samuel, and Pierre Serna.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnimals and civilizationxHistory. 0aAnimals and history. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aBavington, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroglio, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFudge, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandes, Joan B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandes, Joan B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Paula Young, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNovero, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRitvo, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothfels, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSamuel, S